Introduction and History

The SHARE Esprit de Corps session, more commonly known as the SHARE or
HASP sing-along has been a fixture at SHARE meetings for over 30
years.  It is traditionally held on Thursday night of SHARE week in a
corner of the ballroom in which SCIDS is held.  It is probably the
most widely and consistently attended session at SHARE except for the
General Session and is certainly one of the longest running regularly
scheduled sessions in SHARE history.  The sing-along tradition began
informally when a small group of loyal HASP users (the predecessor to
JES2) and IBMers would gather in one corner of SCIDS around a piano
to sing old camp songs and familiar melodies with lyrics they had
"adjusted" to topics appropriate to HASP and SHARE.  In the spring of
1970 in New York the sing-along appeared for the first time in the
SHARE agenda under the title HASP Project Esprit de Corps.  The
sing-along has had its share of ups and downs.  A few SHARE meetings
have been without the session for one reason or another and most of
the original organizers and supporters have left the industry,
retired, or no longer attend SHARE.  But for the most part the
tradition has grown and remained a high-point of SHARE week.  Some of
the song lyrics in this book may seem a bit mysterious and arcane to
many of you newer to the "systems" business and SHARE.  Back in the
"good old days" we sang about "readers" and "writers" and pseudo-DDs,
green cards that were really green, SYSGENs3 and IPLs4.  Today the
lyrics are more up-to-date.  We no longer sing just about HASP (or
JES2) but about everything from DB2 and Rolm phones, to personal
computers.  In fact, some people say you can get a good sense of the
history of the information processing industry over the last twenty
years just by thumbing through the pages of this song book.  The songs
in this book, those which we actually sing at the session, are popular
melodies taken from such diverse musical areas as Broadway musicals,
Rock, Opera, Country/Western, Top 40, Pop and Folk.  These songs have
"enhanced" lyrics written by SHARE members about their favorite topic:
hardware and software system products.  Everyone at SHARE is invited
to turn a creative hand to producing new songs for our session.  While
there are no restrictions on what tunes can be used, the most
successful offerings are those melodies instantly recognized by most
people and that are very "singable".  Of course "singable" is a
relative term.  Lyrics should be topical, about software and hardware
systems, and should fit the meter and phrasing of the song.  Lyrics
should be in good taste.  Profanity and libel are unacceptable and
proper names (especially last names) are discouraged.  Humor, puns,
jokes, and onomatopoeia are strongly encouraged but difficult to
achieve (and harder to spell).  Prizes, peer acclaim and a place in
this book await the authors and songs judged best at each SHARE
meeting.

Submitting Songs

Song submissions are accepted starting Monday of SHARE week and may be
delivered to the Esprit de Corps mailbox in SHARE Headquarters anytime
during the normal hours of that office.  All submissions must be
delivered by 12:00 Noon on Wednesday of SHARE week.  The last pickup
from the mailbox will be made at 12:30PM on Wednesday afternoon.
Songs received after that will be held over to the next SHARE meeting.
Song submissions may also be delivered directly to the Session
Speaker, the JES2 Project Manager, or a JES2 Project Deputy.

Preference for Electronically Submitted Lyrics

Preference will be given to song lyrics that are submitted in machine
readable format, on appropriate media, and in suitable format
(described below).  Song  lyrics that are submitted on paper
(including punch cards, cocktail napkins, and the like) will be
considered for use only if time to prepare them for display is
available.  Paper submissions that are not used at the current SHARE
meeting may be converted to machine readable format and held over to
the next SHARE meeting.

Media

Submissions will be accepted only 3.5" HDD diskettes.  The diskette
should be labeled as shown below and must include a title line
specifying the SHARE meeting date with the words "Song Submission" and
at least your name and installation code.

SHARE Song Submission 02/22/1998
(6 Songs from 4 authors)

John Doe (IWC)
International Widget Corporation
123 Sesame Street
Mid Town, MA 02135

Information Processing Center
Mail Point 3-N-90A

Content

Each diskette may contain as many song submissions as you wish and
these submissions need not all be from the same author(s) or
installation.  Each song submission must be a separate PC DOS ASCII
text file.  Songs formatted according to the rules described below are
preferable, though any song submitted as a DOS ASCII text file will be
considered in machine readable format.  Regardless of the format of
your submission, to be eligible each song file must contain at least:

* A title, source, or other information that identifies
  the melody being used. If the song is unusual or likely to be
  unfamiliar to the organizers of the sing-along you must attach sheet
  music to your submission. (Please observe relevant copyright and
  royalty laws when copying sheet music.

* The names and installation codes of the authors of the "enhanced"
  song lyrics.  Anonymous submissions are permitted but should be
  designated as such in lieu of supplying an author's name.

Conventions and Notation

When typing your song lyrics there are some conventions you should
observe to help make your song suitable to be displayed and sung.
This notation helps people know how you intend the lyrics of the song
to be sung in relation to the melody.  Mostly, normal punctuation and
spelling is used.  Each verse of the song is written as a series of
lines similar to the lines of a poem.

Emphasis, Expansion, and Contraction

Sometimes a longer word in the new lyrics for a song are is used to
replace several shorter words in the original lyrics.  When this is
done the meter and phrasing of the song may require that some or all
of the syllables in a word be emphasized or sung individually.  In
these cases the individual parts of a word to be sung are set off with
hyphens.  For example, if "in-tu-it-ively" were written then each
hyphenated section of the word would be sung separately.  Contractions
are indicated with apostrophes.  Apostrophes can be used anywhere in a
word, even before the first letter to drop syllables that are not
sung.  For example, "Because" is often contracted as "'Cause"
(pronounced "kuz").  Contractions are also common at the end of words
such as "workin'" (working) or "SHAREin'" (SHAREing).  Sometimes a
syllable in a word should be held across several notes.  Holding can
be used when your wording has fewer syllables than required by the
songs phrasing, but this should be avoided when possible.  Held
syllables are usually indicated using hyphens and/or repeated letters
or ellipses at the end of a line.  For example, "AaaaBEND..." is held
long at the end of a song, or "paging" might be sung with an elongated
"a" sound.

Pronunciation, Spelled Words and Numbers

When words are spelled out in capital letters separated by hyphens,
the spelling of the word is sung.  For example, "S-C-A-T" would be
sung as "es-cee-a-tee".

If a word is capitalized but not hyphenated, such as "SYSGEN" or
"APAR" then the conventional pronunciation used in data processing
parlance will be sung.  In this case "sis-jen" and "ay-par".

If an alternate or unconventional pronunciation is desired or if a
word is uncommon then specific singing instructions may be included as
a parenthetical remark in the song text.  For example: CICS (say
kicks).

In most cases numbers in songs are sung according to the same
convention as capitalized words.  For example, 360 would likely be
sung as "three-sixty".  Where it is not clear how a number should be
sung or to make certain that a number is sung as required it is better
to spell out the pronunciation.  For example, "ninety-six-seventy-two"
instead of 9672.

Song Tag Language

In the past, overhead transparencies were also produced from DCF
Script input files.  More recently, a set of display programs that
drive a video graphics projector has been used as the SHARE Esprit de
Corps session.  These methods depend on a special set of SCRIPT tags
designed specifically to format songs.  While it is not required, if
you wish, you may "mark up" your song submissions with these tags to
assist us in preparing your song for display.  The tags are defined as
DCF (SCRIPT) macros and operated like normal DCF tags.  Some tags,
like SONG, VERSE, CHORUS and REPEAT are used to delineate parts of the
song.  For printing or display they control appropriate formatting and
pagination.  Other tags, like SONG, BY and KEY are used to format
indexes and the table of contents in the printed song book and to
create catalogs for the song display programs.  Some tags that permit
character string operands such as titles require that the parameter
strings be enclosed in single quotation marks if the string contains
blanks and/or if more than one string parameter is present.  For
example:

.SONG 'My Country Tis of Thee' 'God Save The Queen'

If a character string operand contains a single quotation mark (or
apostrophe) then each single quotation mark is entered as two adjacent
single  quotation marks.  For example:

.SONG 'There''s No Business Like Show Business'

SONG


.SONG 'title' ['subtitle']

The SONG tag is used to begin a song and specify the title of the song
and optional subtitle.  The information on the SONG tag in your file
should be the original title of the song (if you know it) or something
that will give people a clue as to what melody you intend the lyrics
to fit.  The optional subtitle can be used to specify an alternate
name for the song or further information that will help identify the
song's melody such as:

.SONG 'Suicide is Painless' 'M*A*S*H TV Theme'

.SONG 'If I Only Had a Brain' 'from the Wizard of OZ'

The SONG tag is used to indicate the title at the top of a song in the
song book or at the top of the screen on the display.  Any optional
subtitle will appear in italics after the main title.  The SONG tag is
also used to create index and table of contents entries in the song
book and catalog entries used by the song display program.  There
should only be one SONG tag in any DOS ASCII text file that you
submit.

BY


.BY author-information

The BY tag is used to include the names and installation codes of song
authors in the song file.  BY tags are used only in producing internal
catalogs and statistics.  Authors names are not included in the song
book or displayed by the song display programs.  You may include as
many BY tags in song files as there are authors of your "enhanced"
lyrics.  The author-information specified may be anything and need not
be enclosed in quotation marks.  You should include at least the
authors first and last names and their SHARE installation code.  If
your song submission is to remain anonymous then you should include a
BY tag with the string "ANONYMOUS" in place of the author's name.

VERSE


.VERSE <'optional title for medleys'>

The VERSE tag is used to delineate the verses of a song.  Each verse
of the song, including the first, should be preceded by a VERSE tag.
In addition to beginning each verse, a title may be used in a medley
where the melody of each verse may be different.  The VERSE tag is
used to control pagination and scrolling in the song book and display
program respectively.  When the optional title is specified in a
medley verse the optional title is included as a title on the printed
or displayed verse.

CHORUS


.CHORUS

The CHORUS tag is used either to store a repeating chorus verse or to
repeat a previously stored chorus verse.  When the same wording is
used over and over again in the song as a chorus the CHORUS tag should
be used.  However, if each chorus of the song is sung with slightly
(or greatly) different wording then the choruses are treated as normal
verses and the VERSE tag must be used.

The first time the CHORUS tag is encountered all the song lines
following the tag up to the next CHORUS or VERSE tag are saved.  Then,
every time a CHORUS tag is encountered the saved chorus is
automatically inserted in the displayed song.

For example, in the song "It's A Small, Small, World (No. 1)" printed
below, the chorus beginning "It's a HASP world after all..." would
appear after each verse since a CHORUS tag appears after each verse.
Note also, that the CHORUS tag before and after (and terminates) the
saved text of the chorus is necessary to make the chorus appear after
the first verse.

.SONG 'It''s A Small, Small World (No. 1)'

.VERSE
It's a world of paging, a world of swaps,
It's a world of staging and multidrops,
Though I'm running JES-2 on my new C-P-U,
It's a HASP world after all.
.CHORUS
It's a HASP world after all,
It's a HASP world after all,
It's a HASP world after all,
It's a new HASP world.
.CHORUS
.VERSE
We can SHARE our SPOOLs,
We can fill our queues,
On our U-P, A-P, and M-P-Us,
Although I-B-M says
that its new name is JES,
It's a HASP world after all.
.CHORUS
.VERSE
To improve response and remove distress,
JES-2 runs the show under M-V-S.
Though it's now called JES-2,
It's a HASP world after all.
.CHORUS
REPEAT


.REPEAT

The REPEAT tag is used in very short songs to cause the entire song to
be sung a second time.  In the song book the notation "(REPEAT)" is
printed at the bottom of the song.  The display program recognizes the
REPEAT tag and scrolls the display of the song a second time with an
appropriate comment.  The REPEAT should always be the last tag in any
song to be repeated.


