And now a new Ex-tended version
means one more time 'round with this mess.

Cross Memory is new arch-i-tecture,
that extended addressing at last.
If only I could understand it, and figure out why it's called DAS.

They've added some new I/O features.
The one that they call "channel queue",
can handle concurrent instructions, as long as it's no more than two.

Another great I/O enhancement is titled "resume and suspend".
They use it to write channel programs,
that do paging I/O without "end".
chorus
That do paging I/O without "e-e-nd".
That do paging I/O without "end".
They use it to write channel programs, that do
paging I/O without "end".

