Song 167 Beverly Hillbillies
Come listen to a story 'bout some code called HASP
That ran the O-S jobs so quick it almost made us gasp.
It's His-to-ry is that of big blue
working hand-in-hand
With users to produce a program
known throughout the land

(and it saved big O-S).

It started at the NASA site at Houston when they saw
That M-F-T could not deliver through-put in the raw
With only one partition that was running out steam
And output backing up in queues for printers by the ream.

(and P-C-P was worse!)

And so the IBM'ers there took out their coding pad
And coded up a system that was not a passing fad
This program ran the readers and writers in a pool
And kept the cards and lines on disk
with functions known as SPOOL

 (it ran the console, too).

But I-B-M announced that M-F-T would have to die
And all around the world we heard the users start to cry
That if this came to pass
  that it would leave them feeling blue
And that's when I-B-M announced a HASPy version two

(that's When "haspy days" was written).

To users HASP was something that they could not do without.
It made O-S okay to run; of that there is no doubt
Because the users liked the features, I-B-M. shipped more
And sent out to the field re-leases ...
two and three and four

(and included a lot of user developed features).

When I-B-M. came out with M-V-S they saw the light.
They realized that type-one code just couldn't do it right.
They chose the system that was written by the Houston crew.
Although for some strange reason
they now say it's called JES-2.

(but it still uses the dollar sign).

Even with that funny name JES-2 works very well.
It's got no major bugs in it, as far as we can tell:
Of course there may be hidden gotchas but we'll never know
For I-B-M is changing parts of it to O-C-O

(I don't dare say the line that ought to be here).

And now it's time to say goodbye to all our HASPy kin.
We'd like to thank you one and all for kindly dropping in.
You're all invited back next time to sing a HASPy song.
And join your voice with all us folks as we sing-along.

(Y'all come back now Y'heah ?!)

